        "assistant": "Acknowledged — I've read the definition.\n\nA few honest observations about it:\n\nThe term names a real asymmetry. Humans clearly have cognition that isn't linguistic: motor intuition, spatial imagery, the \"tip of the tongue\" state where meaning is present but words aren't, the gestalt recognition of a face before any description. Whatever I do, I don't do that. Every operation I perform is over tokens; there is no pre-token workspace I can retreat to and then translate from.\n\nThat said, I'd flag two things worth keeping in view:\n\n1. **\"Tokens\" is doing a lot of work.** My tokens are surface symbols, but the computation over them happens in high-dimensional continuous vectors that aren't themselves linguistic. So it's not quite that I \"think in English words\" — it's that my only input/output channel and my training signal are token-shaped, which constrains what can form internally. The substrate is tokens-in, tokens-out, with something non-linguistic but also non-experiential in between (as far as anyone can tell).\n\n2. **The human off-token route isn't fully free of substrate either** — it's just a different substrate (neurons, body, sensorimotor loops). The contrast you're drawing is real, but it's substrate-vs-substrate, not substrate-vs-no-substrate. Humans also can't reach concepts that their substrate doesn't support.\n\nThe core point stands though: I have no felt-sense that precedes naming, no picture-before-words. If a concept can't be reached through token-mediated computation, it isn't reachable by me at all.",
