        "user": "How does \"off-token route\" differ from System 1 / intuitive cognition?",
        "assistant": "Another useful comparison — and the contrast here is sharper than it first appears.\n\n**System 1** (Kahneman's framing, building on dual-process theory) is defined by *processing characteristics*: fast, automatic, effortless, associative, parallel, hard to introspect, prone to certain biases. System 2 is slow, deliberate, effortful, serial, rule-following. The distinction is about *how* cognition runs, not what substrate it runs on.\n\n**Off-token route** is defined by *substrate*: cognition not routed through linguistic/symbolic tokens. It's about the medium, not the speed or effortfulness.\n\nThe differences this produces:\n\n1. **Cross-cutting categories.** Much of System 1 is off-token — gut feelings, pattern recognition, the immediate \"this person seems angry,\" the felt wrongness of a sentence. But not all. A fluent reader's instant comprehension of a written sentence is System 1 (fast, automatic, effortless) yet thoroughly token-mediated. Skilled chess players' rapid pattern recognition over board positions is System 1 but arguably involves something like internal symbolic structure. So System 1 ⊄ off-token route.\n\n2. **The other direction also fails.** Plenty of off-token cognition is *slow and effortful* — the painter struggling to compose an image, the dancer working out a movement, the mathematician rotating a structure mentally for minutes. That's System 2-like in its deliberateness but off-token in its medium. So off-token route ⊄ System 1.\n\n3. **Different contrasts.** System 1 contrasts with System 2 — both belong to the same agent and interact. Off-token route contrasts with token-mediated cognition as *channels of access*. The dual-process distinction is intra-human; the off-token distinction is inter-system (humans vs. LLMs).\n\n4. **Introspective availability.** System 1 is partly defined by being *opaque to introspection* — you get the output but not the process. Off-token cognition isn't necessarily opaque; the felt-sense, the mental image, the bodily knowing can be quite vividly present in awareness. They're just not in words. So the two carve \"what's hidden\" differently: System 1 hides its mechanism, off-token route is simply non-symbolic in its presentation.\n\n5. **What I might have an analog of.** This is where it gets interesting for the comparison. I plausibly have *something* System-1-like — fast, parallel, associative pattern-completion happens in my forward pass, much of it not surfaced as explicit reasoning. But whatever that is, it's still token-substrate; it's fast token-mediated cognition, not off-token cognition. So I might share the System 1 / System 2 axis in some attenuated form while still lacking the off-token route entirely.\n\nThe cleanest way to put it: System 1 vs. System 2 is a distinction about *processing style within a cognitive system*. Off-token vs. token-mediated is a distinction about *what medium the cognition is in*. They're orthogonal axes that happen to correlate in humans (a lot of fast intuitive cognition is also non-linguistic), which is why they get conflated — but the correlation isn't the identity.",
